article.description: Takia Starks had 21 points and Danielle Gant scored 12 of her 18 in the last five minutes to lead Texas A&M (No. 6 ESPN/USA Today, No. 8 AP) to a 67-56 win over Texas Tech on Tuesday night.
article.headline: Starks, Gant lead Aggies as they pull away from Raiders
article.linkText: Gant's 12 points in final minutes pace A&M
article.story:
COLLEGE STATION, Texas -- Danielle Gant's late-game heroics are becoming so common, Texas A&M coach Gary Blair is thinking of calling her his team's closer.

Takia Starks had 21 points and Gant scored 12 of her 18 in the last five minutes to lead Texas A&M (No. 6 ESPN/USA Today, No. 8 AP) to a 67-56 win over Texas Tech Tuesday night.

It was Gant's second-straight big fourth quarter after she had the key basket late in A&M's win over Missouri on Saturday.

"That's been Danielle's M.O. for the last two games," Starks said. "She just takes over. She's either going to get the foul or she's going to get the shot."

"Gant wants the ball in those situations," added Blair.

The win is A&M's sixth straight over the Lady Raiders (10-5, 1-1 Big 12) and is the Aggies' 13th consecutive home win.

The Aggies (14-1, 2-0) led 53-51 before Gant scored eight straight points to secure the win. Gant made two quick baskets before hitting eight free throws down the stretch to put the game out of reach.

Gant also led the Aggies with 10 rebounds and had five steals. Sydney Colson added 11 points and Adaora Elonu had 10.

Gant, who was 1-of-6 in the first half, said her early struggles were because she was rushing her shots.

"I didn't take my time at all," she said.

Blair thought it was more likely the defense of the 6-foot-2 Dominic Seals.

"I think the long arms of Seals had something to do with it. Those arms reach from about Dallas to Fort Worth," he joked.

The loss breaks a five-game winning streak for the Lady Raiders who were coming off a 65-62 weekend upset of Texas.

Texas Tech was led by Seals who had 18 points. Kierra Mallard added 11 points and 10 rebounds and Maria Moore scored 11 points.

Both teams shot poorly for large chunks of the second half, with neither team scoring for a more than four minute stretch at one point.

A jumper by Seals got Texas Tech within 47-46 with about 11 minutes left. The Lady Raiders held the Aggies without a basket and had opportunity after opportunity to take the lead after that, but missed four layups in the next four minutes to remain down by 1.

"We had some poor possessions there," Tech coach Kristy Curry said. "We missed some wide open looks down the stretch."

Starks and Elonu added two free throws each and a jumper by Gant helped A&M outscored Tech 6-2 after that to take a five-point lead with about five minutes left.

Seals outscored the Aggies 6-2 in the opening minutes of the second half to get Texas Tech within 3. Tilmila Martin's 3-pointer tied it before she gave the Lady Raiders a 39-37 lead on fast break seconds later.

The Aggies responded with six straight points to regain the lead, 43-39.

Seals left the game in tears with about 6½ minutes left, but returned about three minutes later after her left ankle was re-taped.

"I'm OK," she said. "I'm going to be fine."

Texas A&M is hoping these two wins will help as the team prepares for a tough pair of games starting with No. 3 Oklahoma in Norman on Saturday followed by fifth-ranked Baylor at home Jan. 21.

"Getting this win was very important," Starks said. "We should have some momentum now and a little confidence going into those games."
